<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-04-20T23:13:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-04-20T23:13:00-05:00" n="521" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/4342: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJK1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-04-21T13:00:00+08:47"><hi rend="italic">April 21,
                                        1919, 1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 22, 7:26
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>239. Supplementing my cipher telegram number 230, April 17th [<hi rend="italic">18th</hi>], 5 p.m. British cruiser <persName><hi rend="italic">Kent</hi></persName> has returned from America Bay
                            where she fired about 60 shells, 6-inch, at persons presumed to be
                            prepared to resist landing of Omsk Government troops going to <pb facs="0602" n="490" xml:id="pg_490"/> rescue of comrades Vladimir
                            Alexandrofka. Hostility against Allies caused by such action by Great
                            Britain will be felt not by Great Britain but by others as she cannot be
                            attacked on sea and apparently will not have troops guarding
                            railway.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CJK1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>